value.value: Autologous lymphocytes transduced with a retroviral vector encoding a chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) specific for the tumor-associated antigen human carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA), with potential immunostimulating and antineoplastic activities. Upon administration, the anti-CEA-CAR autologous T-lymphocytes target and bind to tumor cells expressing CEA, which results in the cytotoxic T-lymphocyte (CTL)-mediated cell killing of CEA-expressing tumor cells. CEA is overexpressed in various tumor cell types.

A rare, well circumscribed, non-encapsulated tumor that arises in the oral cavity, most often the anterior tongue.  It is characterized by the presence of round to spindle cells in a chondromyxoid or hyalinized stroma.  Recurrences have been observed in a minority of patients.
A benign myoepithelioma characterized by the presence of a minor ductal component.

label.value: Malignant Mixed Tumor, Not Otherwise Specified

value.value: A malignant myoepithelioma characterized by the presence of a minor ductal component.
A phosphaturic mesenchymal tumor with benign histologic features.  It may recur locally but does not metastasize.  Complete excision is curative.

A phosphaturic mesenchymal tumor characterized by the presence of nuclear atypia, high mitotic activity, increased cellularity, marked pleomorphism, and necrosis. It usually develops in lesions that have recurred locally and metastasizes to other sites.
A tumor with perivascular epithelioid cell differentiation characterized by the presence of cords of neoplastic cells in a densely collagenous stroma.
A tumor with perivascular epithelioid cell differentiation characterized by the absence of pleomorphism and scarcity or absence of mitotic figures.

A usually large and aggressive tumor with perivascular epithelioid cell differentiation characterized by the presence of marked nuclear atypia, pleomorphism, increased mitotic activity, necrosis, and infiltrative margins.  The most common metastatic sites are liver, lungs, lymph nodes, and bone.

A term that refers to a heterogeneous group of uncommon soft tissue sarcomas that do not show an identifiable line of differentiation using currently available technologies.  This is a diagnosis of exclusion and includes undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma (also known as malignant fibrous histiocytoma), undifferentiated spindle cell sarcoma, undifferentiated round cell sarcoma, and undifferentiated epithelioid sarcoma.
A questionnaire developed by the European Organisation for Research and Treatment of Cancer (EORTC) consisting of 20 questions designed to assess quality of life in brain cancer patients.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt that they had setbacks in their condition.
An undifferentiated soft tissue sarcoma characterized by the presence of a malignant spindle cell infiltrate with amphophilic or palely eosinophilic cytoplasm.
An undifferentiated soft tissue sarcoma characterized by the presence of uniform round or ovoid malignant cells with a high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio.

A macrocyclic lactone. Rhizoxin binds to tubulin and inhibits microtubule assembly, thereby inducing cytotoxicity. This agent also may inhibit endothelial cell-induced angiogenic activity, which may result in decreased tumor cell proliferation. (NCI04)
A question about whether an individual's outlook on the future has or had worsened.
A question about whether an individual has or had double vision.
An undifferentiated soft tissue sarcoma characterized by the presence of a malignant cellular infiltrate with epithelioid morphology.

label.value: Have Difficulty Reading Because of Vision

value.value: A question about whether an individual has or had difficulty reading because of vision.
An undifferentiated soft tissue sarcoma which cannot be further characterized.

label.value: Have Weakness on One Side of Body

value.value: A question about whether an individual has or had weakness on one side of the body.
A question about whether an individual has or had difficulty speaking.
A question about whether an individual has or had trouble communicating their thoughts.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt drowsy during the daytime.
A question about whether an individual is or was bothered by itchy skin.
A question about whether an individual has or had weakness of both legs.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt unsteady on their feet.
A question about whether an individual has or had trouble controlling their bladder.
A laboratory finding indicating that the line of differentiation in a cellular infiltrate cannot be identified.
A patient-reported outcome measure designed specifically to evaluate the financial distress experienced by cancer patients.

label.value: Have Enough Money to Cover Cost of Treatment

value.value: A question about whether an individual knows they have enough money in their savings, retirement, or assets to cover the cost of their treatment.

label.value: Out-of-Pocket Medical Expenses are More Than Expected

value.value: A question about whether an individual's out-of-pocket medical expenses are more than they thought they would be.

An orally bioavailable, small molecule inhibitor of certain class I phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) isoforms and mammalian target of rapamycin kinase (mTOR) in the PI3K/mTOR signaling pathway, with potential antineoplastic activity. Samotolisib inhibits both certain PI3K isoforms and mTOR in an ATP-competitive manner which may inhibit both the PI3K/mTOR signaling pathway in and proliferation of tumor cells overexpressing PI3K and/or mTOR. The PI3K/mTOR pathway is upregulated in a variety of tumor cells and plays a key role in promoting cancer cell proliferation, and survival, motility and resistance to chemotherapy and radiotherapy. mTOR, a serine/threonine kinase downstream of PI3K, may also be activated in a PI3K-independent fashion; therefore, this agent may be more potent than an agent that inhibits either PI3K or mTOR alone. In addition, LY3023414 may inhibit DNA-dependent protein kinase (DNA-PK), thereby inhibiting the ability of tumor cells to repair damaged DNA. DNA-PK is activated upon DNA damage and plays a key role in repairing double-stranded DNA breaks.

label.value: Worry about Future Financial Problems as a Result of Illness or Treatment

value.value: A question about whether an individual worries or worried about the financial problems they will have in the future as a result of their illness or treatment.

label.value: Feel No Choice about Amount of Money Spent on Care

value.value: A question about whether an individual feels or felt they have no choice about the amount of money they spend on care.

label.value: Frustrated Cannot Work or Contribute as Much as Usual

value.value: A question about whether an individual is or was frustrated that they cannot work or contribute as much as they usually do.
A question about whether an individual is satisfied with their current financial situation.
A question about whether an individual is able to meet their monthly expenses.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt financially stressed.

label.value: Concerned about Keeping Job and Income

value.value: A question about whether an individual is or was concerned about keeping their job and income, including work at home.

label.value: Cancer or Treatment has Reduced Satisfaction with Present Financial Situation

value.value: A question about whether cancer or treatment has reduced an individual's satisfaction with their present financial situation.

label.value: Feel in Control of Financial Situation

value.value: A question about whether an individual feels or felt in control of their financial situation.
An abnormal enlargement of an organ, particularly an organ of the abdominal cavity.

An orally bioavailable 4-thio modified 2-deoxycytidine analog, with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon administration of 4-thio-2-deoxycytidine (TdCyd), this cytidine analog gets incorporated into DNA during replication and inhibits the activity of DNA methyltransferase 1 (DNMT1), which blocks DNA hypermethylation. This results in DNMT1 depletion, hypomethylation of DNA, and the reactivation of tumor suppressor genes that were silenced by hypermethylation; this results in antitumor activity and an inhibition of tumor cell proliferation.

An inhibitor of the Bromodomain and Extra-Terminal (BET) family of proteins, with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon administration, mivebresib binds to the acetyl-lysine binding site of  BRD-containing protein(s), thereby preventing the interaction between those proteins and acetylated histones. This disrupts chromatin remodeling, prevents the expression of certain growth-promoting genes, and leads to an inhibition of cell growth in susceptible tumors.
